See manual_full_00_README.txt for the tier legend before reading this file.

[TV-001-array-construction-mixed]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = [.user, .projects[]]
INPUT = {"user":"stedolan", "projects": ["jq", "wikiflow"]}
GOLD = ["stedolan", "jq", "wikiflow"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": [ [ "$.user" ], "$.projects" ], "transform": "flatten" } }
COMMENT=PYRUN, revised: list-concat in Python sidesteps the shape-first array-literal mismatch flagged in the original proposal (row 15). No OUT_FMT since jq's [...] collects into a single output here (unlike BF-023 below, same expression but streamed).

[TV-002-array-construction-mapped]
LEVEL=py
JQ = [ .[] | . * 2]
INPUT = [1, 2, 3]
GOLD = [2, 4, 6]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {}, "body": "$py= _ * 2"}}
COMMENT=STREAM+PYRUN combo: this one IS a plain map (default-shape foreach over the root array, per-item body), so unlike TV-001 it doesn't need the array-collect mismatch. GOLD is a real array (not reshaped-from-stream) since jq's own [...] already collects it into one array literal here -- worth double-checking whether that changes whether OUT_FMT=STREAM applies at all, since there's no comparison-as-a-stream question when jq itself only emits 1 output.

[TV-003-object-construction-shortcut-stream]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=stream
JQ = {user, title: .titles[]}
INPUT = {"user":"stedolan","titles":["JQ Primer", "More JQ"]}
GOLD = {"user":"stedolan", "title": "JQ Primer"} {"user":"stedolan", "title": "More JQ"}
JFTL = { "main": {"$": true, "foreach": { "value": "title", "in": "$.titles" }, "body": { "user": "$.user", "title": "$title" }}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM, revised: a single Python comprehension builds the whole result array (sidesteps curated-108's object-literal-body question and the nested-field-iteration question), OUT_FMT=STREAM unwraps it. Doesn't test jq's {shorthand} key syntax specifically -- that's now purely a jq-side parsing detail, invisible once translated.

[TV-004-object-construction-computed-key]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = {(.user): .titles}
INPUT = {"user":"stedolan","titles":["JQ Primer", "More JQ"]}
GOLD = {"stedolan": ["JQ Primer", "More JQ"]}
JFTL = { "main": { "$": true, "body": [ [ "$.user", "$.titles" ] ], "transform": "from_pairs" } }
COMMENT=NOT PORTABLE BY DESIGN, same example and reasoning as curated-batch 109 (JFTL keys are structural constants).

[TV-005-recursive-descent]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .. | .a?
INPUT = [[{"a":1}]]
GOLD = 1
JFTL = TODO
COMMENT=BLOCKED: recursive descent needs to walk an arbitrary-depth structure and collect/stream every node -- no foreach shape or navigation form covers unbounded-depth traversal. Tempting to reach for $pyrun with a recursive Python helper, but I don't know whether $pyrun supports multi-statement function definitions or only single expressions (only ever confirmed single-expression use, e.g. 104c's slice) -- not guessing further given how load-bearing this one would be.
